198
00:16:46,040 --> 00:16:50,640
talked about instead of doing what we just talked 
about. For companies that have some sort of scale  

199
00:16:50,640 --> 00:16:56,520
and product market fit, to me the place where I 
see people getting tripped up most often is the  

200
00:16:56,520 --> 00:17:02,840
concept of marketplace liquidity or how to match 
the health of a marketplace. To me, liquidity is  

201
00:17:02,840 --> 00:17:09,040
how marketplaces win. It's this measure of your 
ability to match buyers and sellers efficiently,  

202
00:17:09,040 --> 00:17:13,640
it's how quickly and efficiently people can find 
what they're looking for on your platform. So,  

203
00:17:13,640 --> 00:17:19,160
you can picture a Venn diagram. One circle 
is this is what supply wants to sell,  

204
00:17:19,160 --> 00:17:23,560
and another circle is this is what 
demand wants to buy, and your liquidity  

205
00:17:23,560 --> 00:17:28,920
is the overlap between those two circles.
So for, let's take the example of Lyft or Uber,  

206
00:17:28,920 --> 00:17:34,760
because we talked about them. It might be for all 
the people who open the app with the intention  

207
00:17:34,760 --> 00:17:40,920
to book a ride, how many of those actually 
turn into a ride? And this metric liquidity,  

208
00:17:40,920 --> 00:17:44,880
it's a direct multiplier on the efficiency 
of your marketplace. It's literally at the  

209
00:17:44,880 --> 00:17:50,000
center of your vision, it's why you exist as 
a marketplace is to connect the two. And it's  

210
00:17:50,000 --> 00:17:54,760
also the ultimate engagement loop. The more 
supply you have, the more choice people have,  

211
00:17:54,760 --> 00:17:59,080
the better the services, the more likely it is 
that it turns into a transaction and the more  

212
00:17:59,080 --> 00:18:04,520
likely it is that they come back. And so, it's 
really this incredible circle. And what I see  

213
00:18:04,520 --> 00:18:11,960
is people missing how critical this component is 
in the marketplace, struggle to define it for the  

214
00:18:11,960 --> 00:18:17,680
business, and most importantly struggle to build 
an actionable playbook against it. Like, "Okay,  

215
00:18:17,680 --> 00:18:21,360
how do I manage this? Okay, it's important, 
but what do I do about it?" Basically.

216
00:18:21,360 --> 00:18:26,120
Is there a metric you recommend people 
