306
00:26:24,720 --> 00:26:29,480
Awesome. I'd love to know if there's any examples 
you can think of, of bad marketplace ideas that  

307
00:26:29,480 --> 00:26:33,640
people have tried, but I'll summarize the 
three points you just made, which I love. So,  

308
00:26:33,640 --> 00:26:38,320
these are signs that this is a great opportunity 
for marketplace business, that there's a lot of  

309
00:26:38,320 --> 00:26:45,800
fragmentation on both sides. There's not just 
a small number of companies or customers on one  

310
00:26:45,800 --> 00:26:51,400
side or the other, because if there are, why do 
they need you? There's five airlines or whatever,  

311
00:26:51,400 --> 00:26:58,320
you don't need a marketplace to match with an 
airline. Then two is there's uniform needs,  

312
00:26:58,320 --> 00:27:01,440
the needs are basically consistent. 
I just want to stay in a home, I want  

313
00:27:01,440 --> 00:27:06,560
a car to take me somewhere, I want a plumber.
And then there's a barrier, there's complexity  

314
00:27:06,560 --> 00:27:12,280
to the matchmaking and helping someone book 
the thing, work with them. Finding a car,  

315
00:27:12,280 --> 00:27:15,840
I imagine is like, I'm not going to just 
flag down a car. There's challenge there.  

316
00:27:15,840 --> 00:27:19,480
I'm not going to just go and ask someone, "Can 
I stay in your home?" There's challenges there.

317
00:27:19,480 --> 00:27:20,360
Exactly.

318
00:27:20,360 --> 00:27:22,240
Awesome. Are there any examples 
of companies you've seen that are  

319
00:27:22,240 --> 00:27:25,040
just like, that will never work as a marketplace,  

320
00:27:25,040 --> 00:27:29,000
or here's a funny example of a marketplace 
that tried to be a marketplace and it's not ...

321
00:27:29,000 --> 00:27:34,920
I don't have a great example of that, but I 
can give you a tangentially related example  

322
00:27:34,920 --> 00:27:41,960
of a marketplace that I don't want to throw 
anyone under the bus. I respect the company  

323
00:27:41,960 --> 00:27:46,960
and the effort, but Sidecar at the time 
was another ride-sharing company competing  

324
00:27:46,960 --> 00:27:56,000
with Lyft and Uber, and there's, I'm sure a 
whole bunch of lessons there. They ended up  

325
00:27:58,560 --> 00:28:03,360
closing, but I think one really interesting 
direction that they took pretty early on to  

326
00:28:03,360 --> 00:28:08,120
differentiate themselves was, in my 
mind perhaps very naively a mistake,  

327
00:28:08,120 --> 00:28:14,240
they decided to give complete control to the 
user where as a user you had a whole bunch of  

328
00:28:14,240 --> 00:28:20,840
filters. You could decide, "I want a car that's 
at least 2015 or newer. I want a driver that's  

329
00:28:20,840 --> 00:28:27,560
at least this or newer." And so, I think the 
theory was reasonable on paper. It was like,  

330
00:28:27,560 --> 00:28:31,520
"Hey, let's give people more control over it."
But you have those other players out there,  

331
00:28:31,520 --> 00:28:37,800
you have Lyft and Uber, and people feel forced 
in this standardized experience, "We're going  

332
00:28:37,800 --> 00:28:42,520
to compete by giving you the choice, you get to 
decide the experience that you want." I think in  

333
00:28:42,520 --> 00:28:48,120
reality, it just fragments your marketplace even 
further, and you have this hyper fragmentation in  

334
00:28:48,120 --> 00:28:54,640
your marketplace, and I think it hurt their SLAs 
quite drastically. If you think about the ETA,  

335
00:28:54,640 --> 00:28:58,680
when you ask explicitly you're like, "Yeah, 
sure, I want a newer car," and you slide it to  

336
00:28:58,680 --> 00:29:03,840
2020 not realizing that you just lost 10 
minutes because now we had a great driver,  

337
00:29:03,840 --> 00:29:08,840
but they have a Honda Civic from 2018, 
and it's not the special that you wanted. 

338
00:29:08,840 --> 00:29:16,000
So, I think people who build marketplaces tend 
to want to give a lot of control to the users  

339
00:29:16,000 --> 00:29:20,720
because this is what users want, or this is what 
comes up oftentimes in user feedback like, "Oh,  

340
00:29:20,720 --> 00:29:24,920
we have those two distinct group of users. Those 
ones, they really want new cars. Those ones,  

341
00:29:24,920 --> 00:29:29,640
they don't want new cars." And so, naturally you 
have a product team that builds the toggle to get  

342
00:29:29,640 --> 00:29:37,800
the new cars, and I think the mistake is that 
you unknowingly fragment your supply in a way  

343
00:29:37,800 --> 00:29:42,920
that has a much more meaningful impact on the 
health of your marketplace than you suspect.

344
00:29:42,920 --> 00:29:48,680
I think this is another awesome example 
of don't over listen to users and do what  

345
00:29:48,680 --> 00:29:53,680
you think is going to be best for the business, 
and this is not even a marketplace lesson. It's  

346
00:29:53,680 --> 00:29:59,760
just generally you don't want to give users more 
options than they will need to be successful and  

347
00:29:59,760 --> 00:30:04,440
happy. And I think Sidecar did that because they 
were trying to differentiate from Lyft and Uber,  

348
00:30:04,440 --> 00:30:07,280
like, "What can we do differently?" And they're 
like, "Oh, let's give people all these options."  

349
00:30:07,280 --> 00:30:11,640
I think they even let drivers choose the 
price that they're offering their ride at,  

350
00:30:11,640 --> 00:30:15,720
which made it extra complicated. They're like, 
"Oh my God, all these cars at different prices,"  

351
00:30:15,720 --> 00:30:20,640
but I respect their attempt because they 
were just the third wheel, no pun intended.

352
00:30:21,720 --> 00:30:28,440
Ironically, it's almost the opposite advice that I 
usually give to companies who struggle with market  

353
00:30:28,440 --> 00:30:35,000
health, it's if you have different verticals, try 
if possible to open up your supply walls. Your  

354
00:30:35,000 --> 00:30:40,080
user is telling you like X, but try to give them 
something that is tangential to what you think  

355
00:30:40,080 --> 00:30:46,360
they want, because odds are that they are actually 
fine with it. There's this amazing example from  

356
00:30:46,360 --> 00:30:52,600
Thumbtack, it's the smoke machine example. So 
Thumbtack, now they specialize a little bit  

357
00:30:52,600 --> 00:30:58,080
more in home services, but a few years ago they 
were also doing a lot of events. So, you had DJs,  

358
00:30:58,080 --> 00:31:05,040
you had photographers, and a lot of people 
were hiring for wedding DJs on the platform.  

359
00:31:05,040 --> 00:31:10,200
And one of the checkboxes was a smoke machine, 
and it turns out a lot of people are checking  

360
00:31:10,200 --> 00:31:14,160
this. You're like, "Yeah, hell yeah, 
I want a smoke machine at my wedding." 

361
00:31:14,160 --> 00:31:20,600
And unknowingly to them, obviously, only 5% of our 
DJs had a smoke machine, and so you would carve  

362
00:31:20,600 --> 00:31:25,720
out 95% of our supply. And if when we talked to 
users, they were like, "Oh, no, no, I don't care  

363
00:31:25,720 --> 00:31:29,080
that much about the smoke machine. I didn't 
realize that this was automatically going to  

364
00:31:29,600 --> 00:31:36,600
remove half of the supply." And so, work on ways 
to make this checkbox affect the ranking but not  

365
00:31:36,600 --> 00:31:43,080
the actual filtering is a great example of how you 
